<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by EEF (RaD0021)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">EEF </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(RaD0021)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-top-color:#894fbf; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-top:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Overview</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">EEF, the manufacturers’ organisation, is the voice of manufacturing in the UK, representing all aspects of the manufacturing sector including </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">engineering, aviation, defence, oil and gas, food and chemicals</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ith 6,000 members employing almost one million </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">people</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> EEF members operate in the UK, Europe and throughout the world in a dynamic and highly competitive environment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We are responding to this inquiry because R&amp;D and innovation are central to manufacturers’ strategies to compete and grow their businesses. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">More broadly, as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the UK moves from recession to recovery, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">policy needs to put the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> economy on a path </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">towards </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">long-t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">erm sustainable growth. R&amp;D and innovation have a key role to play in achieving this</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, helping companies to compete and grow in new and existing markets. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Although R&amp;D expenditure rose in the last couple of decades, it failed to keep pace with growth in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">GDP in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">19</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">80s and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">19</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">90s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> meaning R&amp;D expenditure as a percentage of GDP fell</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is now some way below the OECD average,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he same is true for Business Expenditure on R&amp;D, which accounts for 64% of the total</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The decline in R&amp;D expenditure </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">as a perce</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ntage of GDP stabilised</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2000s, and was not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">intensified</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> by the recession. Both companies and government focused on R&amp;D expenditure during this time period meaning that – unlike other elements of expenditure – </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> did not suffer markedly from the econo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">mic downturn.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">EEF research shows that companies have the appetite to do more innovation, but a number of challenges </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">persist</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. These include speed in developing innovations, turning innovation into market opportunity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and technical barriers, such as acces</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s to skills, facilities and appropriate finance</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Government support is generally well-targeted towards helping companies overcome </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">these</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> barriers to innovation, and the additional funding announced at the Spendin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">g Round was welcome.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">owever, more could be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">done to improve the certainty and simplicity of support, and aid SME access. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#894fbf; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#894fbf; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-top:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Comments on the NAO review</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">R&amp;D expenditure </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">has a key role to play in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">g</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">rowth and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">ebalancing</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">As the UK </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">moves from recession and into recovery it is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> important that policy puts </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the economy </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">on a path </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">towards</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> long-term sustainable growth, driven more by exports and investment and less by consumption and government expend</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">iture.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">R&amp;D and innovation are critical to achieving this kind of better</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">balanced gr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">owth. Innovation enables companies to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> develop </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">new products and services </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">which can </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">drive sales </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">exports, or improve processes that boost competitiveness.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Progress</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> has been made</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The NAO review showed that total R&amp;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">D expenditure increased by 37% in real terms between 1995 and 2011. Much of this was accounted for by Business Expenditure on R&amp;D (BERD), which accounts for around 64% of the total, and rose by 34% over the same period. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The review also shows that – altho</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ugh BERD remains concentrated amongst large firms – SME expenditure on R&amp;D has risen. In particular, between 2000 and 2011 the proportion of BERD conducted by SMEs rose from 18% to 23%.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Nonetheless, the UK lags behind its competitors when it comes to inno</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">vation</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Even though </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> NAO review show</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s that total BERD has grown, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">as a proportion of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">GDP</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> – at 1.1% – </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it is some way</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> behind competitors such as Germany, where this figure is close to 2%</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Korea, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">where </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it is over 3%.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UK BERD has not kept pace with the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">OECD average</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">BERD as a % GDP</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="480" height="288" alt="" /></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’s lower level of R&amp;D intensity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is partly explained by our </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">industrial makeup, but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">even once this is taken into account, we lag behind competitors</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> What is more</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he last couple of decades BERD intensity has fallen </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in the UK, whilst the OECD average level has risen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> This is a concern, given the imp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ortant role innovation plays in growth</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The reason for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">growing gap in BERD intensity since 1985 is not entirely clear, though</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> it is likely that falling levels of government support over the same period played a role. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In the UK, Government </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">xpenditure on R&amp;D as a percentage of GDP (GOVERD) was a little higher than the OECD average in 1985 – at 0.4% – but has since fallen to just </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">0.16% of GDP, compared with the OECD average of 0.28%.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">OECD research </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">indicates</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that government support does indeed have a role to play in levels of BERD, with direct funding (e.g. grants) and indirect funding (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e.g.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> tax credits) both having a positive impa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ct on business R&amp;D.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The findings of the NAO report – that government funds </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">9% of business R&amp;D – would also support this view.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">While the level of government support </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is likely to have been</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> a factor in declining BERD intensity, there </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">will be other reasons</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">oo. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">For example, R&amp;D is only one measure of broader innovation activity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and firms may have been investing differently</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">esearch by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">NESTA</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> suggests that R&amp;D only covers about 13% of broader ‘intangible’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> investment, and the intensity of this</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> wider</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> kind of investment actually rose steadily through the 1990s.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">More research is necessary to fully understand the reasons behind the fall in the UK’s BERD intensity while this rose in other OECD countries. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The decline in BERD as a proportion of GDP was </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">not intensified by the recession</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The decline in BERD intensity halted in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">early 2000s and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">intensity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> remained more or less stable throughout the recession. This was in contrast with a number of other indicators, such as investment in capital equipment wh</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ich fell markedly during the recession.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">As with the decline in BERD intensity in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">19</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">80s and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">19</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">90s, more research is needed to understand this phenomenon fully, but there are two factors that are likely to have played a role: firstly, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">government support</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> increased during the recession. S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">econdly, innovation and R&amp;D have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">become an integral</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> part of companies’ growth strategies which may have meant they had no choice but to maintain R&amp;D expenditure in the recession.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Government support will have also helped </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">businesses maintain R&amp;D expend</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">iture. As the NAO report shows, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">UK government funding for R&amp;D in UK business increased by £438mn between 2007 and 2011</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">following the establishment of the TSB in 2007</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">Our Innovation Monitor survey</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">showed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none"> that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">manufacturers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">needed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">to innovate throughout the recession to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">meet the demands of their customers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">This has paid off: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none"> survey showed that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">relatively </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none">few manufacturers felt they were falling behind their competitors due to levels of investment in innovation.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:normal; text-decoration:none"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Manufacturers conduct the lion’s share of BERD</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The NAO review shows that manufacturers conduct nearly three</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">quarters of all BERD. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">As such</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the sector will play an important role in any growth in R&amp;D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, indeed,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> manufacturers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> spending on R&amp;D rose by 6% in re</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">al terms in 2011. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">While the pharmaceutical industry remains the most significant sector in terms of R&amp;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">D expenditure, recent years have seen some shifts in sectoral spending. For example, the motor vehicles industry – which accounted for a fifth of growth in BERD in 2011 – spent more on R&amp;D than the aerospace industry for the first time on record in 2011. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">There are signs that manufacturers have the appetite to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">ste</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">p up investment in R&amp;D</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is reason to think that the recent increase</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s in manufacturing R&amp;D expenditure </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">will</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> continue.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> In EEF’s Innovation Monitor 2013</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">73% </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of companies said </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">they planned to introduce new products </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in the next three years, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">compared with 69% in the last three years. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The survey also showed a shift in focus away from satisfying existing markets towards seeking</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> new markets and new customers.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">C</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">ompanies say key con</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">cerns are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> speed to market, turning innovations into market opp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">ortunity and technical barriers</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hile </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">growing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">expenditure on R&amp;D and innovation is important, ultimately, it is the total amount of successful innovation that makes a difference to growth. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Comp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">anies need to be able to make a return on their investments. Although </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">EEF’s Innovation Monitor 2013 found that the majority of manufacturers felt that they </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">were able to do this</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">they</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> continue</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d to report a range of problems, detailed below:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Speed in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">developing innovation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is important for innovative manufacturers, particularly when it comes to satisfying existing customers. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">However</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">consistently comes out as one of the top barriers in EEF’s Innovation Monitor survey</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> this has become more pertine</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nt over time.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nnovation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is a complex process with many hurdles along the way</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> when it comes to the speed of developing innovation, manufacturers are concerned about their performance.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Manufacturers reported concerns about their ability to turn innovat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ion into market opportunity.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> This reflects broader concerns that while the UK excels at research, the commercialisation of this research has historically been weak.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">urning an innovation into market opportunity can be difficult for a number of reasons. For example, customers are not always keen to be the first mover when it comes to buying a new and relatively unknown product. Another issue can be that sales people nee</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d to learn how to sell new products or services, and this can take time. These challenges in turning innovation into market opportunities are a particular issue given that manufacturers expect to use innovation to develop new markets. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Technical barriers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">can include a lack of access to equipment or facilities. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">or example</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> when it comes to testing prototypes, new products and new processes, a company might not be able </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to justify an investment in new equipment until they are sure their idea will work.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Small</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">er</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> companies are more likely to suffer from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">technical barriers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">as they are more resource constrained than their larger counterparts. This is something that is borne out in the UK Innovation Survey</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, which showed amongst companies defined as ‘broader innovat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ors’ those with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">10-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">49 employees were more likely </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">view</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">almost </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">all barriers to innovation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">as ‘high’ </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">than their larger counterparts.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Access to finance</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">did not come out as a key concern in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">EEF’s Innovation Monitor</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> – as most manufac</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">turers will finance innovation internally – </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it is an issue for smaller companies, particularly the very-smallest companies and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">start-ups</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> which tend to be more reliant on external fi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nance. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This was also evident in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">UK Innovation Survey</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, which showed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">smaller companies were more likely than larger companies to view both the cost and availability of finance as barriers to innovation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#894fbf; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#894fbf; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-top:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Key comments on the 201</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Spending Round</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Spending commitments should boost companies’ ability to innovate</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> suppo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rt is generally well-targeted to help companies tackle the biggest barriers to innovation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> discussed in the previous section</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ost manufacturers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">collaborate as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a key way to overcome the i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ssues they face when innovating and a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> large proportion of govern</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ment support, ranging from</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Collaborative R&amp;D through to Knowledge Transfer Partnership</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s and Catapult centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> facilitates exactly this kind of activity.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">However, the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">largest</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> form of support for innovation and R&amp;D is the R&amp;D tax credit, which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cost</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> £1.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">bn in 201</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1/12</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Although the R&amp;D tax credit is received after innovative activity has taken place, it can be a substantial aid to cash flow and therefore provide a boost to future innovation. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Manufacturers are positive about the support that government provides, citing a range of benefits, such as access to skills and expertise. Smaller companies were also likely to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">say </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that support </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">gave them access to funding. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The £185m increase in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">funding f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Technology Strategy Board (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">TSB</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">announced in the 2015/16 Spending Round </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">was</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> therefore</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> an important recognition of the key role that innovation plays in economic growth</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and government’s role in supporting this</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. We are particularly pleased that some </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of the additional funding will be directed towards Smart grants and the developing network of Catapult centres. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Smart grants are well-targeted towards smaller businesses which face some of the most acute barriers to innovation, and the scheme currently s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">uffers from over-subscription and a subsequently low success rates. Additional funding should address this. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Catapult centres are an important initiative that should provide companies with access to cutting edge facilities and expertise. An increased </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">budget will help to address concerns that existing centres were reaching capacity and may not have had sufficient budget to invest in the latest, most up</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">date technology. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The centres must also be accessible to SMEs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">government should consider develo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ping a metric for SME engagement to ensure it is not only larger companies that benefit from the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Finally, although the increased budget for the TSB is a positive step, this must not be a case of “feast and famine” as this can severely damage </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">innovation capabilities. The TSB</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">needs long-term certainty about its funding</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> as many</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> its programmes commit funding four or five years in advance. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> would advocate that the TSB budget is protected alongside the science budget as part of a science and in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">novation ring-fence.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">As well as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">spending commitments, there was some clarification around the de</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">livery of innovation support</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Innovation support should be distributed at a national level: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Keeping innovation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">support </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">at a national level</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, rather than devolvi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ng it through the Single Local Growth Fund, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">was positive. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The move </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">away from regional delivery </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">towards a nat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ional agency </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">reduced the confusion and duplication sometimes evident with regional support.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ubsequent research through our Innovation Monitor has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">found that manufacturers do no</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> view innovation as a local issue. For example, while 48% of companies said that they partnered at a local level, 51% of manufacturers said they were working with overseas organisations. Policy priorities should continue to b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e delivered strategically at a national level.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sector strategies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> to complement not compete with the TSB</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ector strategies are a step towards government taking a more active approach in innovation and commercialisation of new technologies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">but they </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">should</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> not be the only determinant of support </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for innovation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. It is right that the sector strategies should interact with the support the TSB offers and that some of the TSB’s competitions should be determined by these priorities, but the strategies should not i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">mply new constraints on the TSB. To date, the implementation of policy has reflected this but it remains important that the TSB retains autonomy of the competitions it runs and the businesses it supports. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Following the changes to the innovation landscape</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> in the Spending Review, we continue to recommend that the government should:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Protect the TSB:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Announce a long-term commitment to the TSB in a similar way to the commitment announced for the science capital budget; or protect the TSB’s budget along with s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cience, to create a joint science and innovation ring-fence.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Streamline support:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> wherever possible, application processes should be streamlined and the addition of any more diagnostic processes should be avoided. The government should consider an ‘innovat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ion active’ qualification </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> fast-track access to support. This could be based on whether a company is claiming the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">SME</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> R&amp;D tax credit.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Improve SME access to the Catapult centres:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Membership and Intellectual Property models should be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">harmonised</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> across the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> HVM Catapult sites; government should consider developing metrics around SME engagement; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">longer-term, a portion of the Catapult’s core funding could be contingent on a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">certain level of SME engagement.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We also recommend that the definition</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> R&amp;D </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">within the R&amp;D </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tax credit should remain broad and stable, recognising that process and organisational innovation play an important role in the way companies differentiate themselves and compete.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#894fbf; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#894fbf; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-top:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Suggestions into future inquiries on R&amp;D funding</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Based </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">on the preceding discussion, EEF would suggest the two following potential inquiries in UK R&amp;D funding:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.63pt; padding-left:5.37pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Should the UK have a new target for Business Expenditure on R&amp;D as a % of GDP?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The UK has previously had targets for this, and many European countries </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">do. In Germany it clearly drives policy. The UK is falling behind in BERD, is a target the way to overcome this?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">An</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> inquiry should include discussion of why previous </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">UK and EU </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">targets </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">failed to deliver an increase in R&amp;D as a % of GDP.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is a sector-ba</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sed or technology-based approach to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nnovation preferable?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Although the government has started to move down the route of sector-based strategies, what is the best option longer-term</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">How is duplication of resources minimised, and opportunity to support </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">emerging areas of competitiveness maximised?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p></div><br style="clear:both; mso-break-type:section-break; page-break-before:always" /><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#894fbf; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#894fbf; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-top:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix A: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Achieving better balanced growth – a role for R&amp;D</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">A1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">As the UK came out of recession, a consensus emerged that we could not continue to grow in the same way </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">we</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> had done in the previous 15 years. A better balanced economy would be one where growth was based on innovation, investment and trade rather than cons</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">umption.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> At the time, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">forecasters were optimistic that this kind of growth could be achieved, but the recovery did not materialise as expected and business investment in particular remains well below its pre-recession average. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">A2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> EEF </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">published </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">he </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Route to Growth</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, our take on what an Industrial Strate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">gy </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that would deliver better-balance</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> growth </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for the UK should look like.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The central principle was that government should to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> take an economy-wide approach</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> towards </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">creating the climate and conditions </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that would enable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> businesses in all sectors to grow through investment and exporting.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">A3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> UK has significant strengths on which to build, including a diverse and innovative manufacturing base and strong science capabilities. An Industrial Strategy must se</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ek to build on these strengths</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> with a set of clear ambitions which lay out what government is looking to achieve.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">A4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">EEF’s vision for the economy is based on achieving four key ambitions:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">More companies bringing products and services to market</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">– the UK must </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">be a leading destination for innovation to anchor production and compete with rising R&amp;D intensity around the world</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">More globally focused companies choosing to expand in the UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> – the UK must create a dynamic business environment to support high-value inves</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tment and job creation</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A lower cost of doing business</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> – the UK needs a stable, predictable and competitive regulatory environment and cost base to reduce uncertainty, which can act as a brake on investment</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A more productive and more flexible workforce</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> – th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e UK must have the talent that a diverse and agile business base requires to allow businesses to compete internationally</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">A5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The first of the ambitions is particularly relevant as innovation and R&amp;D are necessary to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> develop new products and services wh</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ich can</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> drive sales and exports. In order to understand whether the economy was making progress against this ambition we set out two key metrics</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A return of Business Expenditure on R&amp;D (BERD) to pre-recession levels</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A 60% increase in the number of SMEs claiming</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the R&amp;D tax credit between 2008/09 and 2014/15</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">A6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">While </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">R&amp;D expenditure is not a perfect measure of innovation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it is a valuable metric and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">measured by a range of international comparator countries.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> BERD is a key component of this. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">A7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The SME R&amp;D tax c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">redit indicator is important as R&amp;D expenditure is concentrated in large businesses, and smaller companies face the most acute barriers to innovation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Progress has been made </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">A8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">To date we have seen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">progress against both of these measures. BERD reached pre</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-recession levels after strong growth in 2011 and the number of SMEs claiming the R&amp;D tax credit increased by 49% between 2008/09 and 2011/12.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">A9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Recent improvements to the SME R&amp;D tax credit scheme and the relative stability of its provision through the tax</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> regime will have played a part in the significant increase in the number of companies using the scheme in the past three years.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The tax credit </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">should encourage a virtuous circle of i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nvestment in R&amp;D and innovation, and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the NAO’s report shows that over thi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s same time period there has been a corresponding increase in SME expenditure on R&amp;D.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> For further information how policy could drive better-balanced growth, please see the Appendix.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Source: OECD Available online: </span><a href="http://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/sites/sti_scoreboard-2011-en/06/08/g6-8-01.html?contentType=/ns/Chapter,/ns/StatisticalPublication&amp;itemId=/content/chapter/sti_scoreboard-2011-62-en&amp;containerItemId=/content/serial/20725345&amp;accessItemIds=&amp;mimeType=text/html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/sites/sti_scoreboard-2011-en/06/08/g6-8-01.html?contentType=/ns/Chapter,/ns/StatisticalPublication&amp;itemId=/content/chapter/sti_scoreboard-2011-62-en&amp;containerItemId=/content/serial/20725345&amp;accessItemIds=&amp;mimeType=tex</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">t/html</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Dominique Guellec, Bruno Van Pottelsberghe De La Potterie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> (2003)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">The impact of public expenditure on R&amp;D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Economics of Innovation and New Technology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Available online: </span><a href="http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/10438590290004555"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">h</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">ttp://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/10438590290004555</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> NESTA (2012) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> EEF (2013) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Dynamic Innovation – Innovation Monitor 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Available online: </span><a href="http://www.eef.org.uk/blog/file.axd?file=2013%2f8%2fInnovation+Monitor+August+2013.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.eef.org.uk/blog/file.axd?file=2013%2f8%2fInnovation+Monitor+August+2013.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">19% of manufacturers agreed with the statement “we are falling behind our competitors due to the level of our investment in innovation” whilst 54% of companies disa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">greed. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">2013, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">three quarters of companies said that speed to market was more important than it was in the past.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Only 25% of companies said their performance was good or excellent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">when it came to speed of developing innovations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">while </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">30% of companie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">s thought their performance was poor.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">In EEF’s Innovation Monitor 2013, only 38% of companies rated their performance as good or excellent at turning innovations into market opportunity, though this is an improvement compared with our 2010 survey.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> LSE Growth Commission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">(2013) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Investing for Prosperity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri